I gave this place 2 stars because it falsely advises that on Mondays it offers open mic, when it's obvious that you either have to work there, know the person running the show that night, or possibly bribe the host for a chance to get called up on stage. I went this Monday December the 9th and he pulled two names, comics who I've seen just about every Monday I've been there, out of what was supposed to be a "random" drawing. By 2 names I mean 2 names out of one egg holding names of "guests" who signed up for a chance to be called up to perform. Why not call it what it is and say "After we called up the comics with reserved spots, we'll pull one or 2 names at random for real. If we have time".Every other comic called up that night were also comics I've seen any other time I went on open mic night. I've been there a couple of times because I thought it would be fun to get on stage and tell a few jokes. The joke was that I actually thought open mic meant I had a chance of being picked to perform. It wouldn't be as bad if they at least made sure the comics didn't have the same material they used for the entire month. Aside from that, they usually have pretty good comics and the pizza's not bad. Also, most nights the service is pretty good. It would be nice if they didn't use false advertising, but you get what you pay for I guess. Monday's are only 10 bucks a head usually, just don't expect a chance to get on stage unless you know the guy running the show.

Unfortunately, the worst customer service I've ever experienced in a comedy club.  I do not proclaim to be an expert, but my wife and I do attend stand up comedy frequently whether it be in Vegas, Chicago, New York, or a few clubs in our local area.  When purchasing tickets you have the opportunity to purchase a general admission ticket or a VIP ticket that states "Attendance to the show including priority reserved seating in the first two rows of tables, closest to the stage."  We decided to pay the extra $10 each to sit closer.  The staff made a mocking comment in good humor when we arrived that we are VIP's, which I can appreciate as it is a comedy club and you are looking to establish a rapport and start a good experience for the guest.  Unfortunately, that is where the humor stopped.  We were brought into the club and sat in the fourth row at a table, one of the back areas just shy of the bar.  There were 3 open tables right in front of the stage in which my wife asked me to inquire why we weren't seated there.  When I got up and asked the staff, I received the reply "we had a lot of VIP's book tonight."  When I pointed out the three tables that were open I was told "those are reserved."  I do not expect to be treated like royalty, I am a normal guy in the middle class, but it is apparent that there is priority seating if there is further incentive either monetarily or by knowing someone in this club, as these tables were filled just before the show with people of a much higher clientele.  As I stated, they probably did pay more for their seating arrangement, but it is disappointing when you spend extra money to be seated closer and then get pushed to the back.  As for the comedy, I felt the comedians did great on the night of 6.8.19 but the crowd was terribly uptight and unresponsive which made the show feel awkward.  Again, great job by the comedians, everything else unfortunately resulted in a lackluster experience.  We will be looking elsewhere for our future stand up comedy.

One member of our party ran up finally to see if we could get our drinks and one of the bartenders shrugged him off. We FINALLY got our first round of two drinks five minutes before the show started. The waitress came quickly to get our drinks and we didn’t even have a moment to place an order for more. By that time the WHOLE SHOW was about over anyway. So, kind of ridiculous. I emailed about the situation and received no response.

The hostess checked us in quick (very pleasant) and we were quickly escorted to our table which we shared with two more quests. The beer selection here is not that great, and whatever they are brewing needs more work. Both of us had a hell of a time finding few beers we like and we are all around craft beer drinkers. The good thing I'll say is that it was free admission. Our group came in halfway through a comedy competition between two (amateur) teams of man/woman on each. They had various topics they had to tell jokes about for time periods and audience applause determined winner. One guy on one team was funny, other 3 people were not. Had a few laughs over 20 minutes. Next up until close was an hour or 1.5 of amateurs doing 2-3 minute bits, with about 3-4 regular comics at that club (professional? Semi?) In between. About 2 of maybe 10 amateurs were genuinely funny, some just got crickets. One guy we couldn't even understand. Professionals were a bit better. Almost all the bits from everyone that night were very very crude , about sex, and tons of cursing  One drunk guy at the bar behind the audience starting talking to someone real loudly the last half hour which was really distracting, and none of the employees did anything about it. Finally, I had 2 mixed drinks (gin and tonic) that were $12 each and I've never tasted such terrible gin my whole life. Might have been floor cleaner and not gin! Overall, if you are visiting Chicago and only have limited opportunities to do things while you are there, pay the money to go see a professional comic.

**added update at the end**  I was there tonight with my 85 year old grandmother, 60 year old mother and my best friend. I’m not going to get into everything other then that our server forgot to put in our pizza that we had ordered. 30 mins later, after 3 tables in front of us got their deep dish pizzas, I had asked where our pizza was? (Thin cheese pizza) she replied with “pizza?” So I said “yes the pizza we ordered 30 minutes ago” and she said she’ll check. 4 minutes later comes back and says “I forgot to put in your pizza, what was on it?” I looked at her dumbfounded, turned to my family and said she forgot to put it in, do we still want it. They said no so i relaid the answer and got a “oh, ok” in response before she walked away. No I’m sorry I forgot or anything. Just “oh,ok”. Worst service ever! Not because she forgot, I’m a bartender and I would never leave a table like that, especially after I was the one whom messed up!
